\pard\plain\qj\fi260\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp0\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 Mariiategui wrote in the
 prologue to Valciarcel\'92s Tempest in Los Andes (1927): \'93I remember the unexpected and impressive type of agitator I
 found four years ago in the indigenous from Puno, Ezequiel Urviola. This meeting was the greatest surprise that Peru had
 in store for me on my return from Europe. Urviola represented the first spark of a fire that was to come. He was the revolutionary
 indigenous, the socialist indigenous. Tuberculous, hunchbacked, he succumbed after two years of tireless work. Today it
 does not matter that Urviola does not exist. It is enough that he existed. As Valcaircel says, today the mountains are pregnant
 with spartacus\'94 (Mariiategui in the prologue to Valcaircel 1927:11). The history of the class struggle in Los Andes definitely
 precedes socialism, but most important, the indigenous-cholo peasantry learned to instrumentalize it. Thus, by the first
 quarter of the twenty-first century, the indigenous- cholo peasantry has not only effectively instrumentalized socialism
 (and Marxism) but also environmentalism (Mejiia 2021; 2024), fixing its discursive articulation on the recognition of sensitive
 entities such as mountains, rivers, and lagoons (de la Cadena 2010). As De la Cadena emphasized about the visionary work
 of Josie Mariia Arguedas: \'93[t]he totality, Todas las Sangres proposed an alternative indigenous social movement, a critical
 ally of the modern left, but with its own a-modern hybrid logic. Literacy and modern politics were important, but they had
 to be used and translated selectively, }
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 rather than eradicating
 indigenous customs\'94 (2005:18).}
\par
