{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 Although the institutional
 and military foundations of imperialist domination in Los Andes were settled with the implantation of the monopolistic finance
 capital of the most centralized bank capitalists state trusts of the U.S., through extractive enclaves on the most profitable
 industries in semi-feudal and semi-colonial \'93national-economies\'94 during the period 1895 to 1930. From the beginning
 of the twentieth century, the mining industry in Los Andes was under the almost exclusive control of the U.S. imperialist
 bourgeoisie. Mining was one of the industries where capitalism developed most rapidly, especially in Los Andes, where from
 1895 monopoly capital was directed toward large-scale mining, oil production, and agriculture (Mariategui [1928]2011:245-249;
 Cueva [1977]1999:63- 64; Quijano [1977]1988:114-121).}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\sa280\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brsp0\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 In fact, the struggles of
 the central Peruvian highlands mining workers unions were executing active antisystemic resistance since their genesis with
 the first miners strike against the Cerro de Pasco Corporation (CPC) of January 7, 1919 -inspired in the advancements of
 the proletariat in Europe and the Soviet Revolution of October 1917 (Melgar Bao 2020:132)- until the end of the 1980s. The
 processes of union forma\-tion and politicization of the mining proletariat of the central highlands of Peru went through
 a trajectory of radicalization during most of the twentieth century. This tra\-jectory of radicalization diffused to the
 medium and small mines at the national level, as well as to the mines of the southern highlands -as was evidenced by the
 massacres of 1957 and 1966 in the mines of Toquepala (Moquegua), exploited by the Southern Peru Copper Corporation (SPC)-.
 Mines opened for the \'93nationalization\'94 of the fi\-nance capital of the U.S. imperialist bourgeoisie through the Cuajone
 contract, secretly signed by the \'93nationalist\'94 military government of Velasco Alvarado.}
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f0\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs13\afs13\ul0\super\chftn
