\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 While during the 1980s,
 the co-optation of the mining workers unions of the South\-ern Peru Copper Corporation (SPC) was consolidated as a result
 of the enforcement of its institutionalization trajectory. Meanwhile, the intensity and harshness of the militarism executed
 against the protests of the mining workers in the central Peruvian highlands exploited by the Cerro de Pasco Copper Corporation
 (CPC), evidenced the disruptiveness of the transgression carried out by the mining workers struggles as a direct challenge
 to the main reproduction circuit of capital accumulation. The system\-atic application of militarism is the sole guarantee
 to hold its imperialist policy over the mines of the central highlands of Peru was evidenced in the massacres of Malpaso
 (1930), Cobriza (1971), as well as the militarized repression of the miners\'92 strike cam\-paign of the mid-80s repressed
 with the imprisonment of hundreds of unionized miners, and the assassination of Saul Cantoral in 1988 by the \'93Commando
 Rodrigo Franco\'94 task force (a paramilitary criminal organization for annihilation that operated under the first government
 of Alan Garcia).}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 However, the radicalization
 of the miners\'92 strikes developed facing militarized re\-pression and military regimes. The formation of a vanguard of
 the Peruvian proletariat in open confrontation with the U.S. imperialist mining bourgeoisie, developed until the 1980s,
 when the Communist Party of Peru-Sendero Luminoso (PCP-SL) and the Tu\-pac Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA) began armed
 struggles. The trajectory of radicalization of the struggles of the miners became an anti-imperialist challenge, operated
 in a context characterized by the escalation of the armed struggle in Latin America, by the consequences of the Sino-Soviet
 secession, and the resolution of the imperialists wars between the U.S.S.R. and the U.S.. The formation of the basis for
 the horizontal centralization of Sino-American finance capital developed, gradually after the shared imperialist resolution
 of the Vietnam War, and the subsequent im\-plementation of market reforms in China by Deng XiaoPing in 1978, until the early
 years of the 21st century, marked by the September 11 of 2001 attacks on Wall Street, the Pentagon and the White House.
 When, under conditions of shared imperialism, these financial capitals begin a process of separation and rupture, gradually
 reducing their horizontal centralization. Thus, constraining the inter-\'93nationalization\'94 of U.S. bank capitals as
 finance capital circulating through the economic formations of China\'92s industrial production}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
