{\listtext\pard\plain 4.\'09\tab}
\ls7\ilvl0\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\b\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs20\afs20\ul0 Antimining struggles blocking
 the expansion of the U.S. gold mining extractive frontier in Ca jamarca}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 The expansion of the extractive
 frontier of Minera Yanacocha-Newmont in Cajamarca has been contested by an mining movement that employs what is called a
 unique front strategy. It has proven to be effective in creating sufficient people\'92s social power to confront imperialist
 mining. The harshness of the military\'92s repression against the popular and mainly peasant mining movement in Cajamarca
 revealed the cruelty of the imperialist domination in Peru, just after the democratic election of a president of nationalist
 and military background (Ollanta Humala). The mining struggles in Cajamarca taught us that peasant struggles can be interpreted
 and developed as anti\-imperialist struggles, since they imply a class confrontation between two extremes of capitalist
 accumulation: the international mining bourgeoisie and the indigenous peasantry. The challenge that mining struggles represent
 for the central nucleus of imperialist domination in countries where mining constitutes the main enclave of cap\-italist
 accumulation, points to the strategic nature of the mining struggles. They are the spearhead for the development of an antisystemic
 movement, as well as critical for the geo-economics needs of the dynamics of capital accumulation during the current systemic
 crisis (Veltmeyer 2015:124; Wallerstein 2002:38).}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 The mining struggles for
 the defense of Quilish Mountain and the water sources of Cajamarca in 2004 had shown the effectiveness of the unique front
 strategy: they have joined the efforts of multiple organizations. These include: peasant nightwatch organi\-zations (\'93rondas
 campesinas\'94), irrigation boards (\'93juntas de riego\'94), urban nightwatch organizations (\'93rondas urbanas\'94), the
 teachers union at the provincial and district level (SUTEP-Cajamarca), fractions of the PCP-PR of Cajamarca, and university
 students and environmental NGOs such as Ecovida and Grufides. Since the beginning of the struggle against the Conga mining
 project of Minera Yanacocha-Newmont in Novem\-ber 2011, the environmental defense fronts confronted the government of the
 recently elected president Ollanta Humala who had promised to the peasants that Cajamarca\'92s lagoons would not be destroyed
 nor would mining be allowed without popular consent.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 In this context, the sustained
 mining campaign opposing Minera Yanacocha- Newmont\'92s Conga project escalated, contesting not only to the U.S. gold mining
 com\-pany, but directly the administration and government of the former military captain and President Ollanta Humala. The
 formation of the environmental defense fronts at the beginning of the first decade of the 2000s in Cajamarca was the result
 of a polit\-ical coalition between the environmental NGOs -particularly Ecovida-, the teachers provincial union (SUTEP Cajamarca)
 and the peasant nightwatch organizations then controlled by the PCP-PR, as an effective strategy to unite the popular forces
 in de\-fense of Cajamarca\'92s water sources. However, after some time this coalition lost control of the popular mining
 movement.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 In this context, a new group
 of leaders, composed of radical professional politi\-cians, garnered control of the movement, limiting the role of the PCP-PR
 and the environmental NGOs. Thus, in September of 2010, Celendin\'92s first declaration was made to create the Interprovincial
 Coordinator for the Defense of the Environment, which forged a new strong coalition for mining struggles including second-level
 or\-ganizations of five provinces located in the direct influence area of the Conga mining project (Interview LM2 03/06/2014).
 This coalition would allow coordination between the environmental NGOs, led by Marco Arana (GRUFIDES), and the radical fraction
 of the popular movement of Cajamarca led by Wilfredo Saavedra. As the latter was gaining strength among the peasant and
 urban bases of Cajamarca, bringing together }
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 fractions of the teacher\'92s
 union (SUTEP Cajamarca) and peasant and urban night\-watch organizations (\'93rondas campesinas y urbanas\'94) opposed to
 the control of the PCP-PR, the frictions between these sectors worsened.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 With the formation of this
 new coalition, the sector of Wilfredo Saavedra would be in charge of learning and translating the environmental framework
 to a broader sector of the peasantry, university students and neighborhood organizations. This demonstrated the capacity
 of the radical sector leadership to further broaden the bases of the unique front against the expansion of the extractive
 frontier of Minera Yanacocha-Newmont. The radicalization of the struggle began on November 24, 2011, when the peasants of
 Bambamarca and Celendln took over the lagoons that the Conga Mining Project planned to destroy. This performance of struggle
 required an effective organizational structure that would allow the mobilization and rotation of 200 peasants every two
 days to prevent the machinery of Minera Yanacocha, the police and the military from entering the lagoons and taking control
 of water sources (Interview LM5 03/08/2014).}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 The magnitude of the repression
 carried out by the government of Ollanta Humala crudely demonstrates the operation of mining accumulation by repression
 against the peasantry of Cajamarca. The militarization of Cajamarca was order by decree RS 231-2012-DE, which imposed the
 state of emergency from May 29 to June 25, 2012 in the provinces of Cajamarca, Celendln and Hualgayoc.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 In this context, on July
 3, 2012, during the 34th day of the regional strike (\'93paro regional indefinido\'94) in Cajamarca, the military forces
 killed four peasants in the town\'92s square of Celendln:}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 \'93Here, on July 3, it
 happened that the police and the military were down on the corner [..] when they started shooting at us, then the people
 who were here in the central square [of Celend}
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0\chcbpat17 l}
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 n] began to run through
 different places [...]; and the people [. . . ] took shelter here in the church of the Virgen del Carmen. And when the police
 and the military came [. . . ] wanting to break it down [the door] [. . . ]. The priests were inside [. . . ], the door
 of the church was open to shelter us because if it hadn\'92t been open suddenly more of us would have been killed; but thank
 God the door was open, and we entered, more or less 200 people. We were sheltered inside from around 4[pm]in the afternoon
 until 8:30 at night, until the priest asked the Ombudsman of the Peruvian state to come and get us out: because we couldn\'92t
 go out because the military and the police were full [at] [the courtyard of the church]. [. . . ] And then they thought
 that we had thrown stones at each other, we had killed each other with stones [referring to the fallacious and blatant lies
 of the then Minister of the Interior, who had \'93informed\'94 that the [four] dead in Celendln were a result of stones
 thrown by the protesters themselves]. But it wasn\'92t true because my son had the bullet that had entered his mouth. The
 first helicopter that came, then [. . . ] since he was filming the helicopter, like this [raises an arm and makes the gesture
 of holding a video camera or cell phone pointed at the sky] [. . . ] the bullet had entered through his mouth and had stayed
 [. . . ] in the brain. So that was what they had taken out [in the autopsy] because the little teeth here and the bones
 there [touches his mouth] had been found in his stomach\'94 (SERVINDI 2014).}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 The mobilized groups in
 Celendln marched to the Municipality\'92s building to demand the town Mayor Mauro Silas to stay on the people\'92s side
 in their struggle to defend the lagoons. The shots made by the military from the balcony of the municipal building and from
 helicopters, exhibited the magnitude of the imperialist mining repression. The brutality of the military\'92s repression
 of the popular mining movement in Cajamarca revealed the imperialist nature of the domination exercised by the international
 mining bourgeoisie.}
\par
\pard\plain\tx446\qj\sl271\slmult1\wrapdefault\s64\f1
