{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\b\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs20\afs20\ul0 Obstructing China\'92s copper
 mining under imperialist U.S.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi460\sa240\sl271\slmult1\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs20\afs20\ul0 domination in Apurlmac}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 The cruelty of the imperialist
 repression against the mining workers during the 20th century reveals the magnitude of the repression of the mining struggle
 carried out by the peasantry today, after a century of political mining contention in Peru. The social formation that currently
 directly confronts extractive mining capital is the peasantry, not the mining proletariat. By claiming the defense of water,
 and and life against the extension of the extractive frontier, mining struggles show themselves to be absolutely antagonistic
 to the extractive capitalist accumulation process. That is, as a frontal struggle against the international mining bourgeoisie,
 and even beyond, the mining struggle confronts the capitalist system and the productive and commercial dynamics that sustain
 it on a global scale, blocking its reproduction. Faced with this problem, imperialist domination mobilized the armed military
 forces to enforce the interests of the mining bourgeoisie (Lust 2016:5).}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 On Friday, October 14, 2016,
 two hundred indigenous peasants from the communi\-ties of Choquecca, Quehuira, Allahua, Antuyo and Pumamarca, located in
 the province of Cotabambas (Apurlmac), began a road blockade obstructing the trucks loaded with mineral ore through the
 mining road used by the Chinese capital company MMG Limited Las Bambas. The peasant communities demanded payment from the
 mining company for the use of a communal road within their territories, through which the mine site connects to the main
 mining road and the trucks loaded with mineral ore head to the port of Matarani in the region of Arequipa. The road blockade
 that started that morning was brutally cleared by the police, killing community member Quintino Cereceda Huiza with a bullet
 to the head and wounding twenty more peasants. A few days later, the Minister of the Interior (security) Carlos Basombrlo,
 declared that the police forces were not authorized in any way to clear the road blockade that day (El Comercio 2016:8).}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\sa540\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 The communities of southern
 Cotabambas rebelled against the power of the Chinese mining company MMG Limited Las Bambas for 186 days until April 17,
 2017, when the province of Cotabambas was assigned the state of emergency, authorizing military repression against community
 members. Although the mining struggle of the peasant communities of Cotabambas (Apurlmac) against the Chinese mining company
 MMG Limited Las Bambas did not include expressly an \'94antimining\'94 claim -as in Caja- marca and Cotopaxi- its direct
 target is the imperialist mining company, and indeed the magnitude of the repression executed to secure the interests of
 China\'92s mining bourgeoisie confirms the disposition of the armed forces to serve in shared imperialism conditions to
 guarantee the MMG mining operations by militarism.}
\par
\pard\plain\tx446\li460\fi-460\sa240\sl271\slmult1\wrapdefault\s64\f1
{\listtext\pard\plain 6.\'09\tab}
\ls7\ilvl0\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\b\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs20\afs20\ul0 Historical boundaries for imperialist
 mining militarism at the breakdown meantime of Sino-American shared imperialism: The antimining indigenous-cholo movement
 struggles against the Atico Canadian Mining in Cotopaxi, Ecuador}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\sa380\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 The constitution of the
 antimining national front of Ecuador (Frente Nacional An- timinero - FNA), evidences the outcome of the antimining contention
 scale shift pro\-cess in its conjunction with the processes of polarization and identity formation. The level of coordination
 of the antimining struggles is higher and advanced than twenty years ago, the performances of struggles were emulated and
 adapted with success.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 Recently, only a few months
 ago during March, 2024, the Atico Canadian Mining attempted to pass an illegal socioenvironmental consultation as legitimate
 to claim the exploration of the La Plata project surrounding the indigenous-cholo communities of Las Pampas, Palo Quemado,
 Galapagos, La Florida in Sigchos, province of Cotopaxi. Peasant producers of the best panela of the world and some of the
 better cattles of Ecuador opposed firmly to the militarized celebration of an ilegal and ilegitimate socio-environmetal
 consultation.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 In a context in which the
 debate of the law instrument for the national regulation of the Consultation and Free, Prior and Informed Consent (FPIC)
 as an international instrument adopted by the Constitution of Ecuador of 2008, in complete correspon\-dence with the recognition
 of the rights indigenous peoples and nationalities of the Ecuador, as an historical reform. The indigenous movement most
 important confeder\-ation of Ecuador, the CONAIE, as a member organization of the National Antimining Front of Ecuador (FNA),
 participated in the celebration of a permanent mobilization assembly of the FNA at the national scale, where the mining
 projects are located, in strategic solidarity with the antimining struggle campaign developing during those days in Sigchos,
 Cotopaxi, that left hundreds of peasants and activists injured, and Meslas Robayo Masapanta in coma after receiving a shot
 in the face.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 The social formation which
 is developing with the constitution of the antimining po\-litical identity of the indigenous-cholo peasantry in historical
 resistance is a relational product of the political economy dynamics of imperialism and the perpetual militarism of its
 colonial policy over our territories. By which its antisystemic definition was his\-torically, materially built, and correctly
 interpreted for their own interest as a world antagonist class challenging the top-layer economic formations of the world-economy
 of shared imperialism. Which we identify as inter-\'94national\'94 bank state capitalist trusts in contention, with respective
 differentiated trajectories of concentration and central\-ization, most clearly emphasized at the present time in the Sino-American
 gradual rupture by horizontal decentralization, and its consequences over the decline of the rate of surplus-vale due to
 a relocation of an expected amount of variable capital to other \'94national-economies\'94.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 The use of shields to contest
 the bullets as an human act of life defense when unarmed masses of peasants, students, workers, are being shot by the army
 which is supposed to protect the life of the people but instead guarantee by militarism the reproduction of the finance
 capital beared by the top-layer of the international bank state capitalists. In which hands is accumulated the profit of
 mining capital production and circulation. The monopolist tendency and the fierce competition over the most important branch
 of industry in the world-economy of imperialism are the forces with which the process of horizontal capital decentralization
 of the Sino-American finance capital develops the new imperialist wars of re-partition to a higher point.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 Under conditions of shared
 imperialism, the competition between China and U.S. inter-\'94national\'94 bank state capitalists trusts are evidenced in
 the participation of transnational enterprises as Atico Canadian Mining, a result of vertical centralization by absorption
 of the canadian Toachi Mining Company, to attempt the exportation of gold and copper commodity-capital produced in Cotopaxi
 (Ecuador) to the Quigdao Port in China.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 The risk factors considered
 for March report of Atico Canadian Mining expressed: \'94[t]he Company is exposed to many risks in conducting its business,
 including but not limited to metal price risk as the Company derive its revenue from the sale of copper, gold, and silver;
 credit risk in the normal course of business; currency risk as the Company reports its financial statements in US dollars
 whereas the Company }
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 operates in jurisdictions
 that conducts its business in other currencies. Recognizing indeed, the profits are being severely affected by the currency
 depreciation of the U.S. dollar, as the mining commodity-capital will be in surplus-value form produced with advanced capital
 in the currency of U.S. dollar, as the operations are located in Ecuador. Furthermore, the credit risk augmented as the
 finance capital circulating in the operations of the Atico Canadian Mining in Ecuador should be beared by the China bank
 state capitalist trust for accumulation of their deficit in gold-money-capital compared to the U.S. total gold-capital reserves
 monetized expression in the hegemonic U.S. dollar currency (Figure 3).}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\sa540\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 Finally, but not last, the
 gold and copper price are gradually stopping to grow, due to the incremental tension between Beijing and Washington, due
 to the Palestine- Israel war, the gradual positioning of Russia over Ukraine, the U.K. drop in support\-ing military Israel
 genocide over Palestine civilian, the Iran effective military step-in the Palestine-Israel war, the increasing tension in
 Taiwan and the shameful electoral politics of the most advanced democracy of the world, support the concerns of Atico Canadian
 Mining. Its not an isolated sight or movement, is happening at the same time that the horizontal decentralization of the
 Sino-American finance capital is impacting the profit-seeking decisions of the layers of economic formations above as NVIDIA
 or Tesla.}
\par
\pard\plain\tx446\qj\sa260\wrapdefault\s64\f1
{\listtext\pard\plain 7.\'09\tab}
\ls7\ilvl0\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\b\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs20\afs20\ul0 Conclusions}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 The article shows that antimining
 struggles have an antisystemic effect on the mining circuit of extended capital accumulation, and effectively challenge
 imperialist domina\-tion in Peru. By blocking the expansion of mining\'92s territorial frontier and obstructing the production
 and circulation of mining commodities, mining struggles challenge the mining bourgeoisie and the circulation of its productive
 capital.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 The development of the political
 identity which started to take form during the first years of the 2000s in the firsts antimining campaigns of struggle executed
 by the effective mobilization of the peasantry organizations in Cajamarca (Peru) under the strategy of the constitution
 of a unique front for the defense of the water and land against mining dispossession and destruction, by the diffusion of
 an environmental frame open to its appropriation by the indigenous-cholo peasantry organizations as Las Rondas Campesinas,
 socialist leaderships as the socialist vanguard which radicalized the antimining front during 2010 and 2012, left unions
 as the SUTEP, subnational parties and electoral politicians as the MAS of Cajamarca and the former subnational governor
 Gregorio Santos.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 The effectiveness of obstructive
 mining performances in Peru was revealed at least since 2004, with the success of the mining protests against Minera Yanacocha-
 Newmont and the withdrawal of government authorization to explore the Quilish mountain in Cajamarca. The increasingly radical
 nature of the contentious perfor\-mances by the peasants of Huambocancha Alta and Huambocancha Baja achieved an uninterrupted
 blockade of the access route to Minera Yanacocha-Newmont gold mine, and stalled the police forces sent to unblock it. Although
 it wasn\'92t the first time that highway was blocked during episodes of mining contention in Cajamarca, it is worth saying
 that such the blockade leads to the gradual stoppage of the mine\'92s gold mining activities, significantly affecting its
 production and profits (Mejia 2021:97).}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 Ross (2003:54, 62) points
 out that minerals are a type of natural resource whose transport is relatively easy to obstruct, which has implications
 for the duration and }
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 intensity of extractive
 conflicts. The blockade implied not only the impossibility of access and exit to the mine\'92s facilities, but also the
 expensive use of helicopters for the supply of fuel, equipment, labor and other supplies (Perez Mundaca 2012:70-71). Thus,
 the obstructive performances blocking the Cajamarca-Bambamarca highway ended up drowning Minera Yanacocha-Newmont, proving
 to be an effective performance of struggle for almost the entire duration of the mining campaign for the defense of Quilish
 mountain (Mej}
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0\chcbpat17 i}
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 a 2021:98-99).}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\sa480\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 Innovative obstructive performances
 shared in Apur}
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0\chcbpat17 i}
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 mac and Cajamarca highlight
 how imperialist mining operates in Los Andes. The companies of the international mining bourgeoisies need to establish the
 flow of the extracted mineral either to a smelting plant -such as the Southern Peru Copper Corporation has in Moquegua-,
 or directly to the port of Matarani in Arequipa. As suggested by Ye et al. (2020:7), mining multinational corporations claim
 the monopolized control of the territory and its resources, but also of the entry and exit points from which mineral commodities
 are transported to a port for exportation, finally traded for export, where it completes its conversion into money-capital.
 In this sense, mining and mining struggles in Los Andes effectively block the expansion of the extractive mining frontier
 and obstruct the circuit of the imperialist bourgeoisies finance capital invested in mining. The in\-digenous peasantry
 is actually at the forefront of antisystemic movements challenging the reproduction of global capitalism to defend their
 water, their lands, and their \'93collective self\'94 from imperialist mining.}
