{\cs30\lang1033\langfe1033\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs17\afs17\ul0 The indigenous-cholo peasantry
 struggles against imperialist mining as an antisystemic movement}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 The antisystemic historical
 resistance in Los Andes is indigenous-cholo in its broad base, structurally placed in subordination by the negative dialectics
 of race, which created the international division of labor by the material expansion of the competitive semi-colonial policy
 for mining exploitation, trade, and hoarding of merchant capitals in its attempted transition toward the formation of the
 oligarchic banking bourgeoisies which held the modern world-system under four successive Western inner-transitions since
 the XVI century.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 Antimining struggles in
 Los Andes antagonize these reproduction processes and mechanisms vital for the modern world-system, and the imperialist
 world-economy. If Andean mining struggles decreases the imperialist mining bourgeoisies\'92 rate of profit, it\'92s antisystemic
 effects should have differentiated consequences on the multilevel polity contention among the top-layer of the imperialist
 bourgeoisies ruling the U.S. and the top-layer of the imperialist bourgeoisie ruling China for the expansion of its circuit
 of capital accumulation. At the current breakdown of the modern world-system shared imperialism of Sino-American international
 bank state capitalists trusts, due to its capital horizontal centralization initiated during the \'9270s and held until
 the 2019, when began its horizontal decentralization. The horizontal decentralization process is expressed in the protectionist
 policies adopted by both imperialists bourgeoisies due to an increasing digression of their rate of profit (Figura 2 y Figura
 3). During the breakdown of shared imperialism conditions, differentiated accumulation regimes ruling their capital concentration
 and centralization dynamics are sensible to the dis\-ruption of the circuit of capital reproduction in the strategic industries
 over which the higher rate of profit are made. Mining and particular, gold mining in Los An\-des are core, strategic, metabolic,
 processes of capital production and circulation, Are }
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 structural processes of
 the world-economy of imperialism, the core of the circuit of the capital reproduction of the international bank state capitalists
 trusts, as are their finance capital and its imperialist bourgeoisies (including its domestic managers, the bureaucratic
 bourgeoisies) the ones operating the mines, and the militarism with which they realize its exploitation.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 Indeed, the differentiated
 reproduction outcomes depend on the natural and cultural conditions, expressed in the organic composition of capital at
 each instance of the whole circuit of capital reproduction. The differentiation mechanism operating at the level of the
 rate of profit depends on the transformation of surplus-value into profit at a concrete time of circulation, and expected
 proportions of variable and constant capital consumption, given by the natural, cultural, and -as I argue here- by the historical
 conditions. Manifested in the Andean indigenous-cholo antimining struggles, as historical challengers formed with the constitution
 of the modern world-system and the foundational and metabolic -gold-mining-reproduction processes of the capitalist world-economy.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 The antimining peasants\'92
 struggles in Los Andes of South America effectively ob\-struct the conversion of the money invested as mining productive
 capital by different imperialist bourgeoisies in competition for the extension of its reproduction circuit scale. Employing
 its militarized policy over the territories cursed by the abundance of mineral commodities under different forms of militarism,
 as military and paramilitary interventions in Latin America, or as new imperialist wars as initially expressed in Ukraine
 and Palestine (or sooner Taiwan) ongoing multilevel polity conflicts.}
\par
\pard\plain\qj\fi260\wrapdefault\s64\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\cgrid
{\cs20\lang1033\langfe1033\f1\b0\i0\scaps0\strike0\cf1\expndtw0\charscalex100\dn0\fs22\afs22\ul0 The processes of production
 and circulation of mining imperialist productive capi\-tal had been challenged by proletarian mining workers\'92 struggles
 in China at the coal and lead mines of Anyuan, Pinghsiang County (Kiangsi Province) and Shuikoushan, Changning (Hunan Province)
 between 1921 and 1927; as well as in Peru in episodes of mining contention identified as the massacres of Malpaso (1930),
 Toquepala (1966), and Cobriza (1971). Nevertheless, the cooperation between the peasants\'92 movement and the proletarian
 mining workers in China developed in the Autumn Harvest Up\-rising of 1927. On Octorber of 1928, Mao Tse-Tung led this forces
 to the Chingkang Mountains, and the further armed struggle against Japanese and U.S. imperialism and shared imperialism
 (Mao, [1928]1967:63-69, 81-103). In contrast, the extension of the peasants-workers revolutionary coalition is a matter
 of polemic between historians of the peasants\'92 movement and mining worker\'92s struggles in Peru. The development of
 the peasantry as a class for itself sparked at the final decades of the XX century, the indigenous uprising in Ecuador of
 1990 and the Chiapas liberation by the EZLN in 1994, which preceded the resistance against the expansion of the mining extractive
 frontier accelerated since the first years of the XXI century.}
\par
